<blockquote><p>Fluid ounces (fl. oz.) is a unit of volume, specifically use=
d to measure fluids/liquids in the imperial (UK) or US system</p></blockquo=
te>
<p>? Note: If you were looking to perform calculations with =E2=80=9Counces=
 referred to weight=E2=80=9D you can <a href=3D"https://ovacen.com/en/calcu=
lator/mass-and-weight-conversion/">use the following calculator HERE</a>.</=
p>
<p>Examples of conversion calculation from <strong>fluid ounces to millilit=
ers</strong>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: square;">
<li>To convert one <strong>ounce in ml</strong>, multiply 1 =C3=97 29.5735 =
=3D 29.57 ml.</li>
<li>A small soda can usually contains 330 ml, which would be approximately =
11.16 fluid ounces.</li>
<li>If we want to convert 8 UK <strong>ounces to ml</strong>, the calculati=
on would be 8 =C3=97 28.4131 =3D 227.30 ml.</li>
<li>And if we do it in the US, and if you have 12 fluid ounces and want to =
know how many milliliters they are. The calculations would be: 12 =C3=97 29=
.5735 =3D 354.88 ml.</li>
<li>For the conversion of 16 <strong>oz to milliliter</strong>, simply appl=
y the formula and we would have: 16 =C3=97 29.5735 =3D 473.18 ml.</li>
<li>If you want the equivalence of 33.81 fluid ounces (fl oz) to milliliter=
s (1 liter), the result of the calculations would be 33.81 =C3=97 29.5735 =
=3D 1000 ml.</li>
</ul>
<p>The <strong>fluid ounce is abbreviated as =E2=80=9Cfl oz=E2=80=9D</stron=
g> (most of the time you will see =E2=80=9Coz=E2=80=9D) and is a unit of th=
e imperial or US system, while the milliliter (ml) belongs to the metric sy=
stem. Normally, the US fluid ounce is the most used.</p>
<p>The US fluid ounce (US fl oz) is common in the United States and some co=
untries with cultural or commercial influence from the US. And the imperial=
 fluid ounce (UK fl oz) is used in the United Kingdom and Commonwealth coun=
tries.</p>
